Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the reply from Australia! The Indian players are already out in the middle and they are discussing some tactics. Travis Head and Usman Khawaja are the two openers for Australia. Ravichandran Ashwin has the new ball in hand.
... SECOND INNINGS ...

Australia are ahead in the game, but they know that they cannot be complacent and will need to bat out of their skins on this pitch to take any kind of lead here. The star of the show for them was Matthew Kuhnemann wtih his first ever five-wicket haul in Test cricket. He was well supported by Nathan Lyon who took three wickers while Todd Murphy picked up Virat Kohli once again. It was a good all-round show for them, and now the onus will be on their batters to back up the good job done by the bowlers.

India have been bowled out for just 109 runs! They would be disappointed with their batting effort here. The pitch was tough to bat on as it was spinning a lot, but some of the shots from Indian batters were also not upto the mark. They weren't able to build any sort of partnerships in the middle. The contributions from Virat Kohli, Shubman Gill and a few lusty blows from Umesh Yadav in the end took them over the 100-run mark. However, they would have seen the pitch and with the likes of Ravichandran Ashwin and Ravindra Jadeja in their side, they would surely make batting hard for Australia.

Fuller one around pads, Axar flicks this to square leg and runs the first hard and jogs back for the second but Siraj was not anticipating the second and was jogging around. a good throw from the deep towards the non-striking end sees Siraj short of his crease.
Flighted on leg, Axar Patel defends this off the front foot.
Length dragged back a bit, Mohammed Siraj defends this in front of silly point.
Solid in defense has been Mohammed Siraj so far as he blocks this out too.
Fuller and on off, Mohammed Siraj edges this wide of slip for no run.
Tossed up and on off, Mohammed Siraj defends this.
Mohammed Siraj is the last man in for India.

OUT! Five-wicket haul for Matthew Kuhnemann as he removes Umesh Yadav. On a length and on leg, Umesh Yadav looks to push this to off but gets beaten by the low bounce of this and the ball has hit his pads. Aussies appeal and the umpire had no doubt in raising his finger.
Short in length around middle, Umesh Yadav defends this off his front foot.
Matthew Kuhnemann (8-1-16-4) is back on.

Off-break short in length, Axar Patel defends this off his back foot.

Tossed up around leg, Umesh Yadav goes for the big heave again but misses out and it deflects off his pads.
On a length around middle, Umesh Yadav defends this out.
Fuller around middle, Umesh Yadav drills this back onto the stumps on the non-striking end.
SIX! In the air and it flies over the deep square leg fielder for a maximum. Fuller around pads, Umesh Yadav slog sweeps this for a maximum. Some crucial runs for India.
Full and wide outside off, Axar Patel cuts this to backward point for a single.

Another short delivery, on middle, Umesh Yadav pushes it towards mid off.
Short again and outside off, Axar Patel punches it towards sweeper covers for a single.
On middle, blocked out.
A bit short and on off, Axar Patel moves back and pushes it towards the bowler.
Tossed up, full and on off, turning away, Axar Patel gets beaten on the outside edge as he tries to block.
Slower through the air, on off, Umesh Yadav prods forward and keeps it out to the off side.
Tossed up, full and on off, turning away, Umesh Yadav leans on to defend, but gets beaten on the outside edge. There is another huge shout for caught behind, but turned down.
Floated, full and on off, Umesh Yadav pushes it towards short covers.
Umesh Yadav walks out to replace Ravichandran Ashwin.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Matthew Kuhnemann strikes once more! Ravichandran Ashwin cannot repeat his heroics from his previous games. This is flighted nicely around middle inviting the batter forward, Ravichandran Ashwin obliges and tries to defend, but the turn away takes the slightest of outside edges and Alex Carey takes a sharp catch behind the stumps to his right. He also takes the bails off for the stumping. There is an appeal for caught behind first, but it is turned down and then Australia smartly appeals for the stumping and the square leg umpire sends it upstairs. As per protocols, the umpire have to check everything and UltraEdge shows a spike and Ashwin has to go back to the hut.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Matthew Kuhnemann

This is floated and on middle, Ravichandran Ashwin uses his feet and defends it with the inner half towards square leg, Axar Patel sets off for the run, but he is sent back haflway down the pitch. However, the fielder is a bit late to get to the ball and Patel survives.

Nathan Lyon to bowl from the other end.

A bit short and on middle, Axar Patel moves back and pushes it towards long on for a run.

Fires this one full and down the leg, Axar Patel misses his flick.
Tossed up, full and on middle, Ravichandran Ashwin steers it towards point for a single.

We are back for the second session! The players are making their out to the middle now. Axar Patel and ​​​​Ravichandran Ashwin has the responsibility to build a partnership for India. Matthew Kuhnemann has the ball in his hand.
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

It was Matthew Kuhnemann who started off the proceeding for the Aussies with the wicket of Rohit Sharma and then Shubman Gill. Soon Nathan Lyon and Todd Murphy were introduced too and they both also got into the scheme of things and scalped a few wickets too. Kuhnemann has been the bowler of the session picking up three really crucial wickets well helped by Lyon who also scalped three and Murphy scalped the wicket of Virat Kohli for the third time in three matches. They will be looking to quickly take the remaining three wickets in the second session and then try to outscore India. We can expect some exciting cricket in the second session as well, so do join us at 12.10 pm IST (6.40 am GMT) to catch all the action.

This session belonged to the visitors as India find themselves in a situation of bother with seven wickets down for just 84 runs! The hosts started off well for the first five overs but ever since spin was introduced in the 6th over it has all been Australia. The spinners got into the attack and frame of schemes really quick and shifted the momentum right in favor of the visitors. Wickets kept falling on regular intervals and India has been pinned back by the mighty Aussies. A lot depends on the duo of Ashwin and Axar to where India will find themselves in the game when the first inning ends.
Mitchell Starc attemps the yorker, but bowls a low full toss, on off, Axar Patel mistimes his drive towards short covers. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 1!
On a length and around leg, Ravichandran Ashwin helps it towards fine leg for a run and gets off the mark.
Goes a bit fuller but down the leg side, Ravichandran Ashwin misses his flick and Alex Carey collects it behind the stumps moving to his left.
Mitchell Starc bangs in a bouncer, on middle and leg, Ravichandran Ashwin ducks under it.
Mitchell Starc comes around the wicket and lands this short of a length, on middle, angling in, Ravichandran Ashwin blocks it down the pitch.
Back of a length and outside off, Axar Patel cuts it towards deep point for a single.
Shortish and on leg, Ravichandran Ashwin gets hurried a bit, but keeps it down towards short leg in the end.
Ravichandran Ashwin walks out to join Axar Patel.

He flights this one up, full and on middle, turning in a bit, Srikar Bharat prods forward to keep it out, but he puts his bat behind his pads and the turn in means the ball hits his front pad first. There is a huge appeal for LBW, but turned down. Steven Smith takes the review after some discussion with Nathan Lyon and Alex Carey and it turns out to be good decision as Ball Tracking indicates three reds. India seven down now!
Shortish and around leg, Srikar Bharat tickles it towards short fine leg.
Floated, full and on middle, Srikar Bharat blocks it out down the pitch.
Tossed up and around off, fuller too, Srikar Bharat leans on to defend, but misses and gets hit high on his pads as he ball rolls towards slip.
A bit short and on middle, Srikar Bharat pushes it back to the bowler.

Quicker one, full and on middle, Srikar Bharat knocks it towards short covers.

Darts this one full and on middle, Axar Patel drills it towards long off for a single and gets off the mark.
Flatter, full and on off, grips and turns away, Axar Patel looks to play, but misses it completely.
Axar Patel walks out to join Srikar Bharat.

OUT! LBW! Todd Murphy gets the big fish, Virat Kohli! He flights this up around off, turning in slightly, Virat Kohli prods forward to clip it away, but close the face of the bat early and gets rapped around the pads. There is a huge appeal for LBW, and up goes the finger. However, Kohli takes the review. UltraEdge shows bat involved and Ball Tracking indicates three reds. Virat Kohli has to go back and Australian players are delighted to see the back of him. India six down now!

Aussies appeal for this and the umpire turns this one down but they opt for DRS. The ball tracker shows that the ball was missing the stumps and the on-field decision stays. Australia loses a review.

Beautifully bowled as this goes away with the arm, Srikar Bharat leans ahead to defend this but gets beaten on the outside edge. Alex Carey takes the bails off in a flash but the foot of Bharat is grounded.

Fuller around off, Virat Kohli pushes this to long on for a single.
Way too short on off, Virat Kohli milks this to short mid wicket.

Short in length around the pads, Virat Kohli gently taps this in front for short fine leg and runs a quick single.
Floater outside off, Virat Kohli is quick to hop onto his back foot and defend this back to the bowler.
Fuller outside off, Virat Kohli leans ahead and defends this in front.
Tossed up around off, Virat Kohli defends this right under his eyes.
Fuller around middle, Srikar Bharat pushes this to long on for a single.
Lyon gives it a bit more air on middle, Srikar Bharat defends this to the on side.

Tossed up around off, textbook stuff in terms of defending by Virat Kohli.
Length dragged back a bit, Virat Kohli defends this off the front foot.
FOUR! That's glorious from Virat Kohli. Fuller around middle, Virat Kohli flicks this through the mid wicket channel for a boundary. He is looking relatively comfortable on a tricky track.
Short in length around middle, Srikar Bharat nudges this to mid wicket for a single.
Fuller around off, Srikar Bharat blocks this out.

Drinks! We are witnessing something extraordinary here. India have lost half their side now with only the half of the first session completed. The wicket is really difficult for the batters and Australian spinners have taken full advantage of that. They will be looking to get the wicket of Virat Kohli as they know that could make a huge difference. India needs to build a partnership to get back in the game. An exciting phase of cricket awaits us. Also, Srikar Bharat walks out to bat now.

OUT! DRAGGED ON! Team India is falling apart like a pack of cards here. Short and wide outside off, Shreyas Iyer looks to cut but gets a bottom edge that travels back onto the root of timber and the bails get dislodged. This track is not for the admirers of back foot stroke play as the bounce is a bit up and down here. India goes 5 down in no time and is looking shell-shocked.
Tossed up outside off, Virat Kohli drives this to long off for a comfortable rotation of strike.
Fuller around pads, Shreyas Iyer strides in front and blocks this out to the on side.
Shreyas Iyer comes out to the middle now with India in a bit of a trouble.

OUT! TAKEN! What is happening in Indore? India is in a situation of bother as they lose their 4th wicket without 50 on the score board. Short and wide outside off, Ravindra Jadeja looks to slap this through mid off but hits this straight in the hands of Matthew Kuhnemann at short cover who makes no mistake and accepts this with both hands.
Commentary.Howout: c Matthew Kuhnemann b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Brillant delivery from the gaffer, and Ravindra Jadeja is struck on his crease as he gets hit on the pads, floater with a bit of pace, Ravindra Jadeja jumps onto his back foot to block this but gets beaten by the pace of this. The ball hits his pads and the umpire had no doubt raising his finger to give Jadeja his marching orders. India asks for a DRS as Jadeja thinks he has edged this and the ultra-edge shows a clear spike so umpire NItin is asked to overturn his decision.
Fuller around off, Ravindra Jadeja blocks this out with a front foot defensive stroke.
Tossed up down leg, Ravindra Jadeja works this to short fine leg.
Fuller around pads, Ravindra Jadeja flicks this to short leg for no run.
Another one that keeps low, Virat Kohli makes room and manages to push it towards short covers.

Shorter in length and on off, Virat Kohli moves back and knocks it towards short covers.

A bit short an on middle, Ravindra Jadeja moves back and works it towards short mid-wicket.

Tossed up, full and on leg, Virat Kohli flicks it towards mid-wicket where the fielder dives to his right and gets a hand to it, the ball rolls towards the sweeper cover fence, but Cameron Green chases it and dives to keep it inside. Three runs taken!

Flighted, full and on middle, Ravindra Jadeja looks to play at it, but gets an outside edge past slips towards third man where the fielder chases it down and dives to keep it inside. Three runs taken!
Ravindra Jadeja walks in next.

OUT! TIMBER! Nathan Lyon gets a big wicket now! A dream delivery for an off-spinner. Lyons bowls this quicker, short and outside off, grips and turns in sharply, Cheteshwar Pujara initially goes on the front foot, but then decides to go on the back foot and plays all over it as the ball goes on to rattle the stumps. Cheteshwar Pujara goes back to the hut for a low score and India are in a spot of bother.
Nathan Lyon starts with a tossed up delivery, full and on middle, Virat Kohli clips it towards deep square leg for a single.
Nathan Lyon replaces Mitchell Starc.
A bit short, on off, keeps low too, Virat Kohli watches it through and forces it towards long off for a single and gets off the mark.
Slower through the air, on middle, Virat Kohli knocks it past the bowler towards mid on.
TURN AND BOUNCE! This is tossed up, full and lands around leg, turns away with extra bounce, Virat Kohli looks to flick, but misses and the ball hits Alex Carey around his shoulders.
Flighted, full and on middle, Virat Kohli dead bats it onto the pitch.
Virat Kohli replaces Shubman Gill.

OUT! TAKEN! Matthew Kuhnemann strikes again! Both the Indian openers are now back in the hut. This is floated, full and on middle inviting the batter forward, Shubman Gill obliges and tries to defend on the front foot, but the turn away takes the outside edge and Steven Smith at first slip takes a sharp catch. India two down now!
Commentary.Howout: c Steven Smith b Matthew Kuhnemann

Commentary.Commentary: Tossed up, full and on leg, Shubman Gill looks to flick, but gets a leading edge along the ground towards short covers.
Overpitched and on middle, Shubman Gill flicks it wide of mid on for a run.
On a length and around leg, Cheteshwar Pujara flicks it through backward square leg for a single and gets off the mark.
Full again and on off, Cheteshwar Pujara pushes it towards short covers.
Goes fuller and on off, Cheteshwar Pujara knocks it towards mid off.

Buzzers! This is on a good length and on middle, Shubman Gill tucks it towards short mid-wicket and sets off for the run, the fielder misses his shy at the bowler's end as Gill puts the dive in. However, the back up is not good and the ball races towards the deep extra cover fence for a boundary. Five runs added to the total!
This is on a hard length and on middle, Shubman Gill blocks it down the pitch.
Cheteshwar Pujara walks out to replace the Indian skipper.

OUT! STUMPED! Matthew Kuhnemann draws first blood! Rohit Sharma tries to take on the bowler, but absolutely throws his wicket away here. Matthew Kuhnemann flights this up, on off, turning away sharply, Rohit Sharma skips down the track and goes for the big slog on the leg side, but gets beaten by the turn away and Alex Carey does the rest behind the stumps leaving Sharma halfway down the pitch. He would be disappointed with this shot as there was no need and he could not take advantage of the two lives given to him earlier. India lose their first wicket!
Commentary.Howout: st Alex Carey b Matthew Kuhnemann

Looped up, full and on off, turning away again, Rohit Sharma goes for the sweep, but misses it completely.
BEATEN! This is tossed up, full and on off, turning away sharply, Rohit Sharma looks to block it, but gets beaten on the outside edge.

Nice variation! Mitchell Starc bowls the off-cutter, on off, shaping away, Rohit Sharma is early into his drive and misses it.
This is on a good length and outside off, angling away, Rohit Sharma leaves it alone.

Full again and on middle, Rohit Sharma defends it towards short mid-wicket.
Fuller one and on off, Rohit Sharma drives it towards short extra covers.
On a length and on middle, Shubman Gill blocks it back towards the bowler.

Overpitched and around leg, Shubman Gill drills it towards mid on.
Pitched up, on off, Shubman Gill pushes it towards mid off.

This is fuller in length and around off, Shubman Gill goes for the drive on the up, but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Goes a bit fuller and on middle, Rohit Sharma looks to defend, but gets an outside edge as the ball goes on two bounces towards second slip. The ball is not carrying on this wicket.
FOUR! Rohit Sharma connects this time alright! Mitchell Starc lands this short of a length and outside off, Rohit Sharma accepts the room and punches it through covers for a boundary.
Back of a length and around off, Rohit Sharma tries to cut close from his body, but misses again.
This is on a good length and on off, angling away again, Rohit Sharma plays for the inswing and misses it completely.

Full and on middle, shaping in, Rohit Sharma knocks it towards mid on.
Length again, on middle, Shubman Gill dead bats it to the off side.

Cameron Green starts with a hard-length delivery, on off, Shubman Gill blocks it towards short covers.
Cameron Green steps up to share this red cherry with Mitchell Starc from the other end.

The batting unit for India has struggled a bit, but it is the bowlers who have had the ultimate say in the series. Whatever the team is they will look to continue the winning momentum and get their third win in the bag.

Hello and welcome to all as we bring you ball-to-ball coverage of day 1 of this 3rd Test match between India and Australia from Holkar Cricket Stadium, Indore. India have already taken a 2-0 lead and are very close to making the final of the World Test Championship 2023, whereas Australia will try to show some fight and make it hard for the hosts. The game offers a lot to the lovers of cricket, and this fierce battle would once again light up the eyelids of the spectators.

The Indians ran riots this morning and picked up wickets in a cluster as they managed to scalp 6 wickets giving away just 41 runs. Ravichandran Ashwin and Umesh Yadav stepped up well and managed to break through the lower middle order and the tail in a quick-fire manner. India now trails by 88 runs and they would be looking to get past this without any hiccups, Let us see how the Indian team responds as they will be out in the middle soon with their Second innnings.

We are done with the Australian first innings as they have been bundled out on 197. The Aussies batted well on a track that had a lot on offer for the bowlers and with the quality that India possesses it was a resilient batting display by the mighty Aussies to score hefty. Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne batted really well earlier and brought the team closer to the first-inning score of the hosts. A good cameo from Steven Smith helped the Aussies to score quickly in the last session on Day 1 and might well prove critical in a low-scoring game. Cameron Green and Peter Handscomb continued where they left off on Day 2 and were looking good in the first half of the first session, but once Peter Handscomb was dismissed, we saw another collapse as they lost six wickets for just 11 runs. However, they have a lead of 88 runs which looks like a good one on this wicket. Their bowlers will hope to put on another good show and put pressure on the hosts.

Well, yesterday belonged to the visitors and for the first time in 3 matches, it was a day dominated by the baggy greens. The splendid bowling of Matthew Kuhnemann and co. saw the visitors bundle out India for cheap and the brilliance of Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne made sure that they put India under further pressure with a good lead. A very good morning to all our viewers. We are all set to update you with ball-to-ball coverage of this exciting Day 2 of the third Test between India and Australia from Indore.

Right then, that is it from an eventful Day 1 of this third Test between Australia and India. The visitors are on the front seat, but the hosts have the quality to make a comeback and will be hoping to make some early inroads on Day 2. The action on Day 2 will begin at 9.30 am IST (4 am GMT). Do join us early for the build-up. Until then, Cheers and Goodbye!

Usman Khawaja is up for a quick chat. He says, he is not sure what different he did from others and just played every delivery on its merit and it was really good for him to have a partnership of significance with Marnus Labuschagne. Adds that it was really a spin-friendly wicket and early on with the moisture around the track it spun a lot. Tells that he believes in playing the sweep shot and has no guilt on getting out to it as this is his go-to stroke and another arsenal in his rapiture.

Australia, on the other hand, dominated proceedings right from the start. Mitchell Starc had Rohit Sharma out twice in the very first over, but Australia did not review any of those and gave a couple of lives to Rohit Sharma. Once, Matthew Kuhnemann came into the attack, they got the grip of the pitch as well as the game. They did not let the Indian batters settle in and continued to pick up wickets. They reduced India to 84/7 in the first session and then bowled them out early in the second session. Kuhnemann registered his maiden five-wicket haul in Tests while Nathan Lyon picked up three scalps and Todd Murphy contributed with one. After coming out to bat, they lost Travis Head very early, but did not lose their heads. Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne built a crucial 96-run stand. The latter was dismissed when he was batting at zero, but was saved as Jadeja overstepped. However, both of them got out in quick succession after taking the lead. Steven Smith then came in and played a few lusty blows before falling to a beauty of a delivery from Jadeja. Cameron Green and Peter Handscomb held till the end and will continue for them on Day 2 when they come out to bat and try to extend their lead and take the game far away from India.

After winning the toss and electing to bat first, India got off to a steady start with Shubman Gill scoring runs quickly, but once their skipper, Rohit Sharma got dismissed for an unnecessary shot, it went  downhill for them. Virat Kohli and Srikar Bharat tried to do the repair job, but could not stay there for long. They were ultimately bowled out for just 109 runs. This wicket is not easy to bat as spinners were getting a lot of help, but they could have got some more runs on the board. When they came out to bowl, they picked up an early wicket, but then struggled for a while and allowed Australia to build a big stand before Tea. They created some half-chances, but were not able to hold on and Jadeja also had Labuschagne out bowled, but it turned out to be a No Ball which has been a problem for him in this series. However they changed their lengths in the third session, and once Ravindra Jadeja got rid of Marnus Labuschagne, they restricted the run flow and it was Jadeja who ended up with all four wickets that fell for Australia. They will be hoping to get through this batting line-up as soon as possible and not let them take a significant lead.

That will be Stumps on Day 1! An excellent Day for Australia comes to an end. They lead by 47 runs and have six wickets in hand. A total of 265 runs were scored and 14 wickets fell. However, Aussies have outplayed the Indians in all three sessions and that is why they are well ahead in the match at the moment.

Another good session for Australia! They are still ahead in this game as they trail by 38 runs, but still have nine wickets in hand. They started the session well by getting rid of the tail of India relatively quickly with Matthew Kuhnemann finishing with a five-for. Then they came out to bat with a positive intent, but lost Travis Head early on. A few moments later, Marnus Labuschagne was also dismissed by Ravindra Jadeja, but was saved by a No Ball. After that, he and Usman Khawaja built a good partnership of 59 runs and batted sensibly, rotating the strike well. These two will look to reduce the lead further when they come out to bat in the third session. India, on the other hand, has gone with their spinners to attack, and they have troubled the batters here and there, but they haven't gotten the rewards as expected as only Jadeja picked up a wicket. They have this break to plan out some different tactics and then put pressure on the Aussie batters in the post-Tea session. Join us at 2.30 pm IST (9 am GMT) to see how things pan out.

The Indian batters failed miserably as they couldn't score big and only managed to set a target of 76 for the visitors. Nathan Lyon had a terrific day 2 as he scalped 8 wickets in the second inning and had the Indian batters in his pocket. The first session is the decider and India needs to scalp wickets in really quick succession and repeat the heroics of Day 2 where they took the last 6 wickets giving away just 11 runs. It is a really uphill task barefoot for the Indian bowlers but nothing is impossible in this beautiful game of ours. Let's see what this first session has in offer for us as we are moments away from the start of play.

Hello and welcome to all our viewers. We will bring you the ball-to-ball update on this decisive Day of the third Test match between India and Australia. India is on the verge of a defeat in this Test as they have set a target of mere 76 runs for the mighty Aussies. It would take a gigantic bowling performance from the Indian side to inflict a defeat on the Baggy Greens in this Test. They will have to defend the lowest total ever in the Test history if they are to go 3-0 up in this series.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, that is it from an enticing Day 2 of this third Test between India and Australia. This game is well in favour of the visitors and they should get over the line comfortably if they bat sensibly. The action on Day 3 will begin at 9.30 am IST (4 am GMT), but as you know you can join us earlier for all the build-up. Until then, Cheers and Goodbye!

Cheteshwar Pujara is up for a quick chat. He says the pitch is really tough to bat on and it is not easy to score runs here. One has to keep scoring runs whenever one gets a chance on such tracks. He adds that 75 does not look like a big score but we have to fight as we are in with a chance, to say the least.Tells that as a batter it is really hard to score and the batters have to score at every single opportunity. On his dismissal, he says that he knew that the line would be middle-leg and all he wanted to do was rotate the strike but he clipped one fine to backward short leg and was dismissed by a stunner. Ends by saying that had he stayed a bit longer with Axar Patel they would have managed to score few more and that would have been ideal for the team.

Australia started Day 2 with a lot of hopes and confidence as Cameron Green and Peter Handscomb were at the crease. However, their intent was a bit defensive and they did not score many runs in first session. This approach came back to cost them as they lost their last six wickets for just 11 runs and could only take a lead of 88 runs which looked like a decent one, but they were at a good position to go well past that. However, their bowlers especially the spin trio of Lyon, Murphy and Matthew Kuhnemann bowled really well keeping the Indian batters in check at most times and also picking up wickets at regular intervals. Cheteshwar Pujara turned out to be a thorn for them, but towards the fag end of the Day, Steven Smith took a blinder of a catch to get rid of him which led to a collapse and India got bowled out for 163. Smith was brilliant with his bowling changes as well which kept the Indian batters guessing. Nathan Lyon was the pick of the bowlers with a five-wicket haul and he ended up with eight wickets while Mitchell Starc and Matthew Kuhnemann chipped in with one each. Todd Murphy did not get any wickets but he kept the batters quiet helping his partners to take advantage. They will be happy with their effort and will confident of getting their first win in this series.

Earlier in the Day, India were really good in the second phase of session one as Ravichandran Ashwin and Umesh Yadav destroyed the lower middle order of Australia in no time picking up three wickets each. Their spells helped them to restrict the Aussies from taking a lead over 100. However, their batters could not back up their bowlers and they failed to make any significant impact on this game. Only a miraculous bowling performance can bail out India from this situation. They have the arsenal in their rapture to do so but it has to be a collective effort. India has been bundled out on 163 and Australia needs 76 runs to win when they come out to bat on Day 3.

So we are done with the Indian innings and this has been yet another poor batting performance by the hosts as they have managed to score just 163 runs. The top-order vows continue to haunt India as the top order apart from Cheteshwar Pujara failed miserably today as well. The likes of Rohit, Gill, and Kohli got out without any major contribution. Pujara was the only one who had a plan and executed it out in the field on how to cater to the spin of the Aussies. Iyer came good and was looking really solid until he was removed courtesy of a stunner from Khwaja. No other batter apart from Pujara and Shreyas Iyer stood up and as a result, India is facing eyeball-to-eyeball with defeat here.

Another enticing session comes to an end! India still trail by 9 runs and have six wickets in hadn. They started the session on the back foot as they lost Shubman Gill quite early on, and Rohit Sharma followed soon after. Then Virat Kohli and Cheteshwar Pujara steadied the ship for a bit, but the former lost his wicket when he was looking good. They will hope to use this break and come back with more energy to get through the middle order of India quickly, while the hosts will need a partnership to make a game out of this. Right then, that is from this enticing third Test between India and Australia. The hosts had the chance to confirm their place in the WTC Final, but they failed to take it, and the Aussies registered their first win of the series. However, the action in the Border-Gavaskar Trophy continues as both teams meet for the fourth and last Test at the Narendra Modi Stadium in Ahmedabad, with a lot at stake for the hosts. The action on Day 1 will begin on the 9th of March at 9.30 am IST (4 am GMT), but as you know, you can join us early for all the build-up. Until then, cheers and goodbye!

Nathan Lyon is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for his 11 wickets in this Test. He says that it has been a remarkable Test series and he is proud that he could contribute to get their first win in the series. Adds that if you believe in your best ball, you will get success on wickets like these. Tells that he feels lucky to have bowled and gotten success against some of the best batters like Virat Kohli and Cheteshwar Pujara and he always enjoys the challenge.

Steven Smith, the victorious skipper of Australia says everything was bang on apart from losing the toss. Adds that all the bowlers contributed well and kept taking wickets on a regular basis and then when the team came out to bat, the partnership between Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne was amazing. Mentions that in the second innings, India were going well but Nathan Lyon and bowlers scalped wickets on a regular basis and that helped them to restrict them to as low as they could and this morning the attack by Head and Marnus won them the game so all in all really happy with the game. On his captaincy, he speaks that he felt really good captaining in these conditions after Pat Cummins flew back, the team responded really well to the hiccups from the earlier games and stood up for each other.

Rohit Sharma, the captain of India says that there were a lot of things that did not go their way. Adds that they were not up to the mark with the bat and knows the importance of putting runs on the board in the first innings which they did not. Tells that when Australia took a lead of 90 odd runs, it was on them to produce another good batting performance but they only managed to set a target of 76 which was always going to be difficult to defend. Mentions that this pitch was the hardest to bat on but credits Lyon for his bowling effort and says they were not brave enough. Tells that they will look to play well in the last Test. Ends by saying that things will not go always as you expect, but you will need to learn from them.

Travis Head is up for a quick chat. He says he was just trying to take a step at a time as on this wicket anything could happen. Adds it feels really nice to contribute and the team has helped him a lot to score handsomely. Says that he thinks the team has been doing well throughout the series just that the result hasn't fallen into their court before today. On his partnership with Marnus Labuschagne, he says that they both were calm after the first wicket but that wicket gave them more options in the field to score freely as India felt they had a chance with close-in fielders. Head closes by saying the ball change was not followed by any messaging it was just that they knew the new ball would take some time to grip and they attacked at the right moment.

India were always playing catch-up in this Test and came out to bat for the second time in the hope of a better performance. However, things did not go as expected, and it was only Cheteshwar Pujara who fought a lone battle, scoring a fifty as well. The turning points were the stunning catches from Usman Khawaja and later in Day 2, their skipper, Steven Smith, getting rid of Shreyas Iyer and Pujara respectively, which helped them restrict the hosts to a fairly low total. Nathan Lyon shone with the ball once again with eight wickets. A total of 30 wickets fell on Day 1 and Day 2 combined, and Australia were set a target of 76 when they strided out to the middle on Day 3 to get their first win of the series and they got there with ease in the end.

In reply, Usman Khawaja led the charge for Australia and scored a brilliant fifty. He was well supported by Marnus Labuschagne, who was lucky to be out in the middle as he got dismissed for a duck, but Ravindra Jadeja overstepped. Both of them stiched up a crucial 96-run stand. They ended Day 1 with a lead of 47 runs. Cameron Green and Peter Handscomb extended their lead on Day 2, but they once again suffered a collapse as they lost their last six wickets for just 11 runs. The decision of Rohit Sharma to bowl Ravichandran Ashwin and Umesh Yadav in tandem worked out as they picked up three wickets each while Jadeja got all four on Day 1. The Aussies took a lead of 88 runs, which looked significant on this wicket.

After winning the toss, Rohit Sharma had no doubts and elected to bat first, but that decision soon proved to be a wrong one as the pitch turned out to be very tricky, with the ball turning a lot, which made it really hard for the batters. Mitchell Starc had Rohit out twice in the very first over of the match, but Australia decided not to review them, which did not cost them much in the end. Some contributions from Shubman Gill, Virat Kohli, and Srikar Bharat and a few lusty blows in the end from Umesh Yadav took them to a total of 109 in their first innings. Matthew Kuhnemann was the star of the show for the Aussies with his maiden five-wicket haul in Tests.

Australia did suffer a scare when they lost Usman Khawaja on the second delivery as Ravichandran Ashwin gave some hopes to the hosts. The Indian spinners then bowled well for the first ten overs keeping the score to just 13. But once, they decided to change the ball, it was all Australia as Travis Head and Marnus Labuschagne changed their approach and took on the bowlers and got them over the line quite comfortably in the end. Steven Smith was really impressive as the stand-in skipper for them, and his bowling changes and field adjustments were right on point. The Aussies outplayed India except for the first session on Day 2, and they thoroughly deserve this victory. This will also give them a massive boost in confidence going into the fourth and final Test, and they know that if they get a result there, they can cast some doubt on India's qualification for the World Test Championship Final.

A fine victory for Australia! They have managed to get their first win of the series and makes it 2-1 which also means that they confirm their place in the World Test Championship Final. India will need to go back to the drawing board and focus a bit on their batting to make a comeback in the next Test.
